RSV was identified in 3235 samples through the ISS from week 37 of 2014 to week 24 of 2018 (Fig. 1
). A total of 407 (12.6%) RSV cases were co-detected with other respiratory viruses, mainly Picornavirus (29.5%, 120/407), Coronavirus (11.5%, 47/407), and Adenovirus (10.1%, 41/407). The majority of RSV cases (97%, 3138/3235) were detected through the PLNDII (Table 1
). Furthermore, during the four studied seasons, RSV prevalence ranged from 1.9% to 3.2% (2.5%, 97/3891) in the sentinel ISS and from 14.4% to 27.2% in the PLNDII (20.7%, 3138/16,779).

Demographic characteristics for RSV-positive and negative cases were described (Table 2
). RSV-positive frequency (72.5%, 2343/3230) was significantly (P < 0.0001) higher among children aged <5 years than the one expected if there was not association between age and RSV infection. The sequence of the HVR2 was determined for 542 RSV-positive samples during the 2014/15–2017/18 period. Demographic and clinical characteristics for those 542 patients, including 56 through the sentinel ISS (Table 3
) and 486 through the PLNDII (Table 4
), were described and the association with the RSV subtype was assessed. On RSV cases detected through the ISS, observed RSV-B subtype frequency (86.4%, 19/22) was significantly higher in females (P = 0.012) and in 15–44 years age group (P = 0.037). Samples from RSV cases that were detected through the PLNDII, belonged mostly to children (88.3%, 429/486) and 59.9% (291/486) were aged <6 months. They presented a RSV-A frequency (66.2%, 137/207) significantly (P = 0.015) higher than the one expected. Three hundred thirty-six (69.1%) cases were hospitalized patients. Bronchiolitis in children aged <6 months (62.9%, 183/291) and ILI in adults aged ≥65 years (24.6%, 14/57) were found to be significantly (P < 0.0001) associated with RSV laboratory confirmation. Moreover, observed frequencies of RSV-positive ILI (8.1%, 6/74) and pneumonia (10.8%, 8/74) among children from 13 months to 4 years old were also significantly (P = 0.002) higher than the ones expected. Therefore, these diagnostics were associated with laboratory-confirmed RSV infection among those age groups.

In addition to the 542 samples from the studied period, 20 RSV-A strains from the 2010/14 period were included in the phylogenetic analysis (Table 5
). RSV-B strains before 2014/15 could not be included due to the poor quality of the sequences. Both of subtypes co-circulated during the study period (2014/15–2017/18), being 46.4% (261/562) of samples subtyped as RSV-A strains and 53.6% (301/562) subtyped as RSV-B strains. Most of RSV-A strains belonged to ON1 genotype (89.3%, 233/261). The remaining ones (10.7%, 28/261) belonged to NA1 genotype, which was undetected since 2015/16 (Fig. 2
). All RSV-B strains clustered in two Buenos Aires genotypes, BA9 (92%, 277/301) and BA10 (8%, 24/301), the latter being only present until the 2015/16 season (Fig. 3
).
